body:
I started working in a larger systemverilog codebase and wanted to simulate it using iverilog. But I was getting an error during elaboration. I was able to track it down to the following minimal example:

```systemverilog
package pkg;

typedef enum logic [3:0] { 
    ABC = 4'h0
} enum_t;

typedef struct packed {
    enum_t item;
} w_enum;

typedef struct packed {
    logic [3:0] item;
} w_logic;

typedef union packed {
    w_enum el1;
    w_logic el2;
} foo_t;

endpackage

import pkg::*;

module main();
foo_t val;
endmodule
```

Compiling this with `iverilog -v -g2012 main.sv` gives me the following error message (I stripped the copyright notice):

```
Icarus Verilog version 11.0 (devel) (s20150603-774-g7f95abc6)

translate: /usr/lib/ivl/ivlpp  -v -L -F"/tmp/ivrlg24dc6567c" -f"/tmp/ivrlg4dc6567c" -p"/tmp/ivrli4dc6567c" | /usr/lib/ivl/ivl -v -C"/tmp/ivrlh4dc6567c" -C"/usr/lib/ivl/vvp.conf" -- -
Icarus Verilog Preprocessor version 11.0 (devel) (s20150603-774-g7f95abc6)

Using language generation: IEEE1800-2012,no-specify,xtypes,icarus-misc
PARSING INPUT
LOCATING TOP-LEVEL MODULES
   main
 ... done, 0 seconds.
ELABORATING DESIGN
:0: error: Member el2 of packed union is 4 bits, expecting 0 bits.
1 error(s) during elaboration.
```

I am not too advanced in Systemverilog but from reading the standard and looking at other examples it seems to me the above code should be correct.

One curious thing I noticed it when you take all the struct, enum and union declarations out of the `pkg` package, the error no longer occurs.

I wasn't able to trim down the code any further, for example directly using the enum and logic vector in the `foo_t` union no longer produces the error:

```systemverilog
typedef union packed {
    enum_t el1;
    logic [3:0] el2;
} foo_t;
```

If you need any more information let me know.

I am using the latest commit of iverilog (7f95abc6)

